725300f-b.title: Queens: 39th Avenue - 52nd Street
725300f-b.text:
39th Ave., (foreground) at the S.W. corner of 52nd Street (back
of one story wing) showing in a set of four views the John Morrell
farmhouse. Views one and two look east, and three and four west. Note
this house was destroyed by fire in November 1925. One of its last
owners was one Morgenthaler of New York City. See also other views for
Nmore dats..
March 1924.
Views 1, 2 & 3.
View 41 April 1925.
Eucene L. Ambruster Collection.

725429f-a.title: Queens: 52nd Street - 39th Avenue
725429f-a.text:
52nd Street (foreground, formerly Dickison Street, also Woodside
Ave.), adjoininm the S.W. corner of 39th Ave. (parallel to front of
this house; formerly Middleburg Ave. and also known as Dutch Eills Road.),
showing a rear view of the John Morrell house. See other views for more
data.
1922.
Eugene L. Ambruster Collection.

725430f-b.title: Queens: 52nd Street - 39th Avenue
725430f-b.text:
(1)
52nd Street (foreground, formerly Dickison Street, also Woodside
Ave.), adjoining the S.W. corner of 39th Ave. (front of this house;
formerly Middleburg Ave. and also Dutch Kills Road), showing a rear view
of the John Morrell house, which was destroyed by fire in November 1925.
It was erected in the middle of the 18th Century by John Morrell who
erected a house and a smithy (forge), on the estate of His father-in-law.
John Alburtes. Other owners were John Morrell 1779, John W. Morrell
1852-1860, William Morrell, and Wm. Morgenthaler of New York in 1903.
1922.
Eugene L. Ambruster Collection.
(2)
The same, showing a more extensive view. At the extreme left is
a house located at the B.E. corner of the first mentioned location,
and situated in the old town of Newtown.
April 1925.
Eugene L. Ambruster Collection.
